-- Deduction Theorem (Lambda Abstraction)
--
-- STATUS: CONCEPTUAL (Issue #151)
-- This file EXPLAINS how the deduction theorem works in CredTT. The `derive`
-- statements use `by definition` and `by pi_intro` tactics which are accepted
-- by the parser but NOT semantically verified - they document intended reasoning.
--
-- Classical: If Gamma, A |- B, then Gamma |- A -> B
-- CredTT: If Gamma, x:A |- b:B @ c, then Gamma |- \x.b : A -> B @ c
--         Stability preserved: stable body -> stable lambda
--
-- Example: From x:Nat |- x+0=x, derive |- \x. x+0=x : Nat -> Nat=Nat

-- Classical deduction: move premise into antecedent of implication
-- CredTT deduction: lambda abstraction preserves credence AND stability

-- Premise in context at credence 1
postulate x_nat : x_is_nat @ 1

-- Body derivation at credence 1
derive body : x_plus_0_eq_x @ 1 from x_nat by definition

-- Lambda abstraction preserves credence
derive lambda_result : forall_x_plus_0_eq_x @ 1 from body by pi_intro

-- Stability check: stable body -> stable lambda
stable body
stable lambda_result

-- Now with weaker credence:
postulate weak_body : weak_prop @ c

-- Lambda still preserves credence (and stability)
derive weak_lambda : forall_weak @ c from weak_body by pi_intro

-- KEY insight: Deduction theorem in CredTT is CREDENCE-PRESERVING
-- If the body has credence c, the lambda has credence c
-- If the body is Stable1, the lambda is Stable1

-- This is DIFFERENT from classical where:
-- Deduction always produces TRUE implication
--
-- In CredTT:
-- Deduction produces implication at SAME credence as body
-- No inflation, no deflation, just honest tracking

-- The function type A -> B @ c means:
-- "Function from A to B with credence c"
-- NOT "if A then B with probability c"
-- The credence is about the FUNCTION ITSELF, not the implication
